Hijama, or cupping therapy, is an ancient practice used across cultures to promote healing and well-being. It involves placing cups on the skin to create a vacuum, drawing out stagnated blood and enhancing circulation. Proponents claim relief from pain, inflammation, and stress, while some use it as part of preventive care. Modern cupping blends traditional techniques with sterile, hygienic standards: single-use cups, trained practitioners, and careful skin preparation. While evidence is mixed, many patients report improved comfort and relaxation. If considering hijama, consult a licensed practitioner, disclose medical history, and ensure proper sanitation to minimize risks.
